Implement the private `merge_states/2` function.

It takes two PN-Counter states — a local state and a remote state — each a map of
the form `%{p: g_counter, n: g_counter}`, where each G-Counter is a map of
`node_id => non_neg_integer`. It must produce a new merged `%{p: ..., n: ...}`
state by merging the two positive G-Counters together and, independently, the two
negative G-Counters together.

Merging two G-Counters is done per node by taking the **maximum** of the local and
remote value for that node (use the provided `merge_g_counters/2` helper, which wraps
`Map.merge/3` with a `max/2` resolver). Nodes present in only one of the two counters
carry through unchanged. This per-node-max rule is what makes the merge idempotent,
commutative, and associative — the CRDT properties the counter relies on.

